\par }\pard \qj \fi540\li0\ri0\sl361\slmult0\widctlpar\tx-360\tx0\tx720\tx792\tx1440\tx1584\tx2160\tx2376\tx2880\tx3168\tx3600\tx3960\tx4140\tx4320\tx4578\tx4752\tx5040\tx5544\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs24 NL:\tab 
Now, Cantor Mandel, would you be good enough to tell us a little about when and where you were born and a little about your family background?
\par YM:\tab Dr. Levin, I was born in a small town in Hungary called Csepe.
\par NL:\tab Can you spell that, please?
\par YM:\tab Yes, I will.  C-S-E-P-E.  Ugocsa Comidat.  That's U-G-O-C-S-A Comidat.
\par NL:\tab That's the district?
\par YM:\tab The district.  On March the 3rd, 1904.
\par NL:\tab So this was part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
\par YM:\tab This was part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.  It was in the part of Hungary which was the so-called "religious" 
Jewish part, where we spoke Yiddish and, eh, automatically we learned two, and some of us even three languages when we were small children.  Yiddish was spoken inside as soon as we closed the door.  From the inside we spoke Yiddish only.  As soon as we we
re on the outside, the language was Hungarian and in some cases the Russian, Maloruski, the Ukrainian language.
\par NL:\tab May I ask, why Russian?  What was the Russian influence there?
\par YM:\tab Because there, at that part of Hungary, were many, many Ukrainians who spo
ke Russian, and the pressure was so big, even 50 and 100 years ago, to tear away from mainly Austro-Hungary because they felt that they can't live as nationals.  Their culture, their education, their music, their everything, is oppressed by the Austrian g
overnment.  Therefore, they, in their own homes, just as we Jews spoke Yiddish, so they spoke Ukrainian.
\par NL:\tab Ukrainian, yes, interesting.
\par YM:\tab This, then, shows that that was even in many, many years ago a very highly-explosive part of Hungary.  If they coul
d have, probably, they would have torn away the part of Hungary from the Austro-Hungarian Empire in those days.  This brought another interesting fact.  They were completely influenced by the Church.  Some of them were Catholics; most of them (the non-Jew
ish part, we're talking about) were Greek Catholics.
\par NL:\tab Greek Orthodox.
\par YM:\tab Greek Orthodox.  In both cases, the Church had an immense...eh...
\par NL:\tab Influence?
\par YM:\tab ...power and influence over them, and even when I was a small child, I started to go to }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24  at the age of three-and-a-half.  When I was four and five, I knew very well what it means to be attacked by the non-Jewish students.

\par NL:\tab You already were...
\par YM:\tab They waited for us with sticks and all kinds of things, and we learned to a degree how to fight 
them as well.  This is maybe an interesting point from a point of view when we ask ourselves, how did the things get to the point where they started in 1938 or '39 in Hungary?  But they really and actually started in 1917 and '18 on a big scale when Horth
y and his, eh, people, came and killed plenty of Jews in Hungary proper, and whoever could take advantage of Jews, did.
\par NL:\tab Yes, we want to come to that, because that's an extremely important chapter.  This was part of the reaction against the B\'e9la Kun Comm
unist regime, I believe.  Now, can you say a little more about your childhood, because this would be so interesting.
\par YM:\tab I, eh, was born in an extremely Orthodox religious family.  My upbringing was the old type of Yiddish upbringing.  Eh, and I was four-and-a-half years old, probably, surely not five yet, I started to learn }{\i\fs24 Chumesh }{\fs24 [Pentateuch]}{
\i\fs24 , Chumesh Midrasheh}{\fs24  [Post-Talmudic literature], eh, it wasn't a question of, do I want it?  There were no considerations as far as psychological questions.  This was it, and this is the way we grew up.
\par NL:\tab Can you tell me, eh, excuse me, par-, I think I interrupted you
\par YM:\tab We were seven children at home,
\par NL:\tab Yes, yes,
\par YM:\tab Three sisters and four brothers, of whom by today only one is alive, who came here in 1913, probably the last boat which reached the United...
\par NL:\tab 19-
\par YM:\tab '13
\par NL:\tab '13.
\par YM:\tab That's my oldest sister who lives in Philadelphia.
\par NL:\tab And her name?
\par YM:\tab Her name is Mrs. Helen Borish, B-O-R-I-S-H.
\par NL:\tab And can you give me the names of the other children?
\par YM:\tab Yes, sure.  The sister who followed her was Esther.  She was married to Yaakov Deutsch.  One sister, the youngest sister, died.  She was never married.  She got what was prevalent in those days in that part of the world, }{\i\fs24 
galoppierende Tuberkulose}{\fs24  [consumption] and died before the age of 20.  Her name was Rivka.
\par NL:\tab Rivka.  And the names of the brothers?
\par YM:\tab My brothers, the younger brother, is Yoel, Yoel.  The one following him is Yisrael Dov, or Srulbear, as we called him, and the youngest brother was David.
\par NL:\tab David.
\par YM:\tab Now, my sister's children.  Did I give you the name of Esther?
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Yes, I did.  Esther had three children.  These children are, all three of them, in Israel, are settled there, and there they live.  Yoel, of course, Rivka had no children, Yoel was the first Associate Chief Cantor of the congregation in Zagreb.

\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab He was professor of Hebrew Studies.  The younger brother was also a cantor; they were both my pupils.
\par NL:\tab Is that so?
\par YM:\tab In }{\i\fs24 Chazanut}{\fs24  [studies of religious chants], I mean.  We all went to }{\i\fs24 Yeshivot}{\fs24 
, and the youngest brother, David, David Mandel, died in Israel in 1949.  His, he already got his doctoral degree from the university in Budapest, with a yellow star on his lapel.  He was a graduate of the seminary in Buda
pest, and, was a graduate of the university in Budapest.
\par NL:\tab What a distinguished family!
\par YM:\tab Interesting, maybe--he was a graduate of the, Hebrew gymnasium in Munk\'e1cs, and maybe one distinction which does not apply, maybe, to too many people, is that afte
r he went from Budapest because we were so very active in Zionist works--I wasn't home--he was engaged to a young lady by the name Hava Eisdorfer.  Their wedding was supposed to take place in June in my Temple in Budapest.  I wasn't home, of course, I was
 in labor camp already in 1940-1944, and it never took place, the wedding never took place, of course, but he went with a }{\i\fs24 Kasztner}{\fs24  group...
\par NL:\tab Ah, yes.
\par YM:\tab ...to, eh, Bergen-Belsen.
\par NL:\tab Uh huh.
\par YM:\tab Not only that, because of my activity in Budapest, while I was there for ten years,  my family was called upon to take them along in my absence...
\par NL:\tab Mmm
\par YM:\tab ...and that was, that was wonderful.
\par NL:\tab Oh yeh.
\par YM:\tab These people who you read in this...
\par NL:\tab Yes...
\par YM:\tab  ...Yuri Brown story, they thought of it, because my brother was just as active.  And my brother came to Israel after Bergen-Belsen.  And after all this, and taught for awhile in }{\i\fs24 Gymnasium}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 HaRaeali}{\fs24 
 in Haifa and had an appointment to teach at the university in Yerushalaim [Jerusalem] of all things, Hebrew literature.  And, he never reached that day, because he died in Israel in April of 1949.
\par NL:\tab Now, let's go back a bit.  I'd like to know a little about your parents.  Can you tell me about father and mother?
\par YM:\tab Father grew up, probably, the same way as I did.  He probably started }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24  [chuckles] when he was the age of three.  He was a real Talmud}{\i\fs24  chochem}{\fs24 
 [scholar of Talmud].  Very knowledgeable Jew.  He also spoke these languages, I have mentioned before, perfectly. He had, quite a bit of knowledge in,  in not only }{\i\fs24 Sifrut}{\fs24  [oral law] and, Talmud and }{\i\fs24 Chumash}{\fs24 
 and so on, but he was a Talmud }{\i\fs24 chochem}{\fs24 .  As a matter of fact, he was not, though he was an ordained rabbi by his own }{\i\fs24 rabbonim}{\fs24  who gave him }{\i\fs24 Hatorath Torah}{\fs24 , and }{\i\fs24 Hatorat rabbanot}{\fs24 
, he never acted, never was, a professional rabbi, but he }{\i\fs24 pasket shayles}{\fs24  [decided questions] as they said there, and took care of the }{\i\fs24 Yeshuvim}{\fs24  [settlements] all around us, and Avrohom Mandel was, eh, quite a }{\i\fs24 
bekovedigge}{\fs24 r [honorable Jew].  My mother...
\par NL:\tab Did he, eh, make a living out of teaching, or did he have a separate occupation?
\par YM:\tab No, no, he had fields and was in the, he was a farmer...
\par NL:\tab A farmer...
\par YM:\tab And I, eh...
\par NL:\tab Were Jews able to own land at that time?
\par YM:\tab Yes.  In those days, yes.  My father, who was born in '77, I think, 1877.  That was really the golden period of Hungarian Jews.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab Because then, it was after '48, after the French Revolution and so on.  And all these countries copied to a degree the French freedom, and so on and so forth.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab And that expressed itself in the fact as well for Jews not to have any restrictions.  Jews, as a matter of fact, were allowed to marry non-Jews, for which before they would have been burned on the, you know?
\par NL:\tab Stake, yes.
\par YM:\tab But in those days there was freedom.  So, you could buy a house.  You could get into business, you could, you could own fields and farms and so on.
\par NL:\tab And so, you grew up on the land.
\par YM:\tab Yes, absolutely.
\par NL:\tab Yes.  And was the family fairly comfortable, economically...
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab ...or did you have hardships?
\par YM:\tab You have to know, I mean, if I should go into this, I don't know.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab That in, in that part of Hungary in those days, let's say my days, after 1904, when I grew up to be at least to understand what's going on, 19
10, '11, '12, and '13, '14, and even to '16, there is a river which was never controlled and never, never, put into shape, so to say, which every year brought floods and floods and floods.
\par NL:\tab Mmm.
\par YM:\tab My father became a poor man, I think, between 1910 and 1916.  Poor.  They made out somehow, but they weren't comfortable at the time anymore.
\par NL:\tab But, eh, the land...
\par YM:\tab The land...
\par NL:\tab ...was still his, and...
\par YM:\tab ...belonged...
\par NL:\tab ...and was he able to recover?
\par YM:\tab Yes, some of it, and whatever could be done with it was done.  But comfortable, he was not.  Before his time, and, of course, my recollection doesn't go back to that, all these land, belonged to my mother's father.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab Eh, and presumably he made a very, very comfortable living.  So th
at shows that there must have come some kind of natural causes which made it impossible for them to be comfortable anymore.  My mother, it may be worthwhile to mention, is the daughter of a man who was a teacher in 1830.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.  A teacher in a Jewish school?
\par YM:\tab There was no school.  He probably was a teacher...
\par NL:\tab Tutoring...
\par YM:\tab ...in a }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24 ...
\par NL:\tab Oh, in a }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24 .
\par YM:\tab Where, I don't know.  In a bigger village, 15, 20, 25, youngsters got together and he taught them the same things.
\par NL:\tab So she was an educated woman, too.
\par YM:\tab Ya, she was.
\par NL:\tab About how many Jews lived in your community, Cantor?
\par YM:\tab 36.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab 36 families, and maybe it's worthwhile to mention that the little community of Csepa had at one time close to 30 }{\i\fs24 yeshivah bachurim}{\fs24  in different }{\i\fs24 yeshivot}{\fs24 . 30.
\par NL:\tab Extraordinary.
\par YM:\tab And this is what pushed us.  We wanted to be, to know a little more, and if Chaim knew this much, and got let's say }{\i\fs24 Haftorat Torah}{\fs24 , Moishe wanted to have the same thing, and this is...
\par NL:\tab You were high achievers.
\par YM:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab What were your relations generally with the non-Jewish community?  You've told us about the antisemitism of the children, but, let's say, father's relations with his non-Jewish neighbors?
\par YM:\tab Very respectful.  Very respectful.  Because firs
t of all they depended on him to a degree.  They worked for him to a degree.  But let me talk about two particular cases, and I think this would be reflective on what we are talking, and in answer to your question.  On one side of our house, because we li
ved in a house, a tremendous house, the family who lived alongside of us was the Greek Orthodox family.  They had sons and daughters living in the same place, but I'm talking about the original family.  On the other side they were so-called "Reformed"...

\par NL:\tab Christians.
\par YM:\tab Christians.  We both, we were in the best of...
\par NL:\tab Terms.
\par YM:\tab ...terms.  They both, my mother spoke to the old lady on one side in Russian or Hungarian.  They spoke to each other, they exchanged views, but we knew that inside, deep, ther
e is a certain hatred because they were extremely devout Catholics, Greek Catholic Christians, and they were immensely under the influence of their clergy.  At the time, which I can't remember, at home, we felt that the Reformed Christians, whatever denom
ination the Reformed movement may belong to, they were a little more lenient.
\par NL:\tab Yes, more modern.
\par YM:\tab More modern.  We played together with these boys, with the children all together.  We sang their songs, we went to the same school...
\par NL:\tab So, it was a relatively benign situation.
\par YM:\tab Yes, yes.
\par NL:\tab There were no antisemitic episodes of violence?
\par YM:\tab No, and if they are thinking of acts like this sort, let's say, pogroms and so on...
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab ...they were very, very far from our, from our life.
\par NL:\tab Yes.  And what large town were you close to?
\par YM:\tab We were close to two towns.  One is Anagy Szo'llo's, that's spelled A-N-A-G-Y, second word, S-Z-O-'-L-L-O'-S, and our district capital, let's say, was Halmi, H-A-L-M-I.
\par NL:\tab And did you go into these towns from time to time?
\par YM:\tab Oh, yes, many times.
\par NL:\tab Many times.
\par YM:\tab As a matter of fact, after 1918, when our part of the, our part of Hungary, became Czechoslovakia, I studied in Anagy Szo'llo's.  As a matter of fact, my first }{\i\fs24 yeshivah}{\fs24  was Anagy Szo'llo's.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab I studied with a great man, a great }{\i\fs24 tzaddik}{\fs24  [very pious man], a great man, eh, Yosef Nehemiah Kormitzer.  He was my first }{\i\fs24 rebbe}{\fs24  in }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab And you spoke about your going to school with the non-Jewish children.  Did you then go to the }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24  and to a public school?
\par YM:\tab When I hear parents--and I had the privilege of teaching here in }{\i\fs24 Beth Judah}{\fs24 
 of Logan when I was the cantor for about 18 years--and I hear parents consulting, constantly consulting, how to make Johnny to want to go to school, and to 
want to do things, I'm always reminded of this, of this episode of my life.  We got up at 6 o'clock in the morning, took care of ourselves, even if we were five years old, now took the }{\i\fs24 koss in die hent and gevashen die finger}{\fs24 
 [took the glass in hand, washed the fingers] and }{\i\fs24 gezukt Modeh Ani}{\fs24  [and said the morning prayer], and we went to }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24 
.  And I will never forget it.  And in my profession, many many times it came back, the way we started, to study in the morning, either any one of the }{\i\fs24 Neviim}{\fs24  [Prophets], [sings] "}{\i\fs24 wai be mo--eh--ah--}{\fs24 " That }{\i\fs24 
niggun}{\fs24  [melody], that was beautiful, it was nice, and this was the way we studied, and it was no question that the child will be nervous if I get him up at 6 o'clock in the morning.  That was no problem.
\par NL:\tab This was expected.
\par YM:\tab Right.  Eh, we, we stayed there, and }{\i\fs24 davened}{\fs24  [prayed], had the morning service.  Until 7:30.  Whenever we got there, 7:30.  At 7:30 we went home to have breakfast.  Because no one had breakfast before }{\i\fs24 davening}{\fs24 
, of course.  And we had our breakfast and went to the school, that means, the elementary school, the regular elementary school, where we remained until eleven o'clock.  At eleven o'clock we rushed back to our }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24  and were in the }{
\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24  until 12:00.  Then we studied }{\i\fs24 chumash}{\fs24 , that was the }{\i\fs24 chumash}{\fs24  period.  Then we went back home, had the dinner used to be in Europe, you know, in mid-day.  We had, eh, }{\i\fs24 Mittagmahl}{\fs24 
 [mid-day meal], you know, and at two o'clock we were back in the public school.  We stayed in the public school until 4:00, sometimes 4:15, and as soon as we were dismissed there, we ran back to the }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24 ...
\par NL:\tab Oh my.
\par YM:\tab ...and repeated }{\i\fs24 Neviim}{\fs24  and studied }{\i\fs24 chumash}{\fs24 .  Whoever was ready for it studied }{\i\fs24 Mishnaios}{\fs24 , or }{\i\fs24 Gemura}{\fs24 .  Or whatever.  And we stayed there till about 6:00.  So this way of
 learning, and this way of, of doing things is maybe not modern, but I think it was extremely helpful in our Jewish education.
\par NL:\tab Extraordinary.  Such discipline that you must have...
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab ...lived by.  And the play time was Sunday, I suppose.
\par YM:\tab Play time was Sunday or whenever we could find the time for it.  Play was not, all work and no play was no problem there.  Whenever you could do it, you did it.
\par NL:\tab Squeezed it in.
\par YM:\tab Squeezed it in.
\par NL:\tab Were you musical as a child?
\par YM:\tab Yes.  Musical, not musically educated.  I was never musically educated, because I didn't have the chance.  There were no teachers.  I had a very sweet child's voice as a child.  I knew, of course, how to }{\i\fs24 daven}{\fs24 
.  And I will never forget it.  I was maybe eight or nine years old when I }{\i\fs24 davened}{\fs24  in my, in our own congregation at home in Csepa, }{\i\fs24 maariv}{\fs24  [evening prayer], on eh, }{\i\fs24 Pesach}{\fs24 , }{\i\fs24 Shavuos}{\fs24 , }{
\i\fs24 Succot}{\fs24 , whatever it was.  And eh, and there were, there were those additional prayers, those inserts, we call them }{\i\fs24 marouvis}{\fs24  [evening prayers], }{\i\fs24 lel shamurim}{\fs24 
 [prayers at Pesach night], and so on and so forth.  And I did very well, I, I knew it was no problem.
\par NL:\tab Eight.
\par YM:\tab When I hear people prepare for the }{\i\fs24 Bar Mitzvah}{\fs24  a year or two earlier, I'm just angry, because if we were called and we were eight, nine years old, for a }{\i\fs24 maftir}{\fs24 
 [last reading of the Torah], it was no problem.  I mean, it was, as a matter of fact the children were called as a rule, because that was the only }{\i\fs24 kibbud}{\fs24  [honor] a boy could get in those days, to be called for a }{\i\fs24 maftir}{\fs24 
 [one who reads concluding verses of the Torah portion], because another }{\i\fs24 aliyah}{\fs24  he couldn't get; the }{\i\fs24 shevah korim}{\fs24  [seven readers] had to be adults.  So, we were the additional, an }{\i\fs24 achron}{\fs24 
 [the last], or a }{\i\fs24 maftir}{\fs24 , we could be called too.
\par NL:\tab This was all very natural in the cycle of your life.
\par YM:\tab Yeh.
\par NL:\tab And so your childhood was passed quite happily.
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab And, do you have some memories of the war years?  Did your family have to move out?  Were any, were there any deprivations?
\par YM:\tab No.  In 1914 when
 the war broke out, as you well know now, I was ten years old.  This is just a side line.  I remember exactly the spot where I read the first announcement of Franz Josef [emperor of Austria/Hungary], who said, "I have thought it through very carefully.  I
 
have given it all the consideration, and we must step in..." and so on and so forth, "the war".  The war years I remember very well because there was terrible pressure on all of us.  Because you have to know that we lived right underneath the Carpathian M
o
untains.  And the first lines maybe were about 100 km, which is about 60-65 miles away from us.  But I remember particularly during the war two years, when people who lived at the very end of the Galician part of Austro-Hungary, had to evac-, be evacuated
 and evacuated, and came to us before }{\i\fs24 Pesach}{\fs24 .  What part of the war that was, I don't remember any more, but these people, about 60 families, came into our little community before }{\i\fs24 Pesach}{\fs24 
, and I will never forget it.  Everyone was put up.  At families, my father, }{\i\fs24 zichronah l'bracha}{\fs24  [of blessed memory], gave a special, gave special permits to use on that }{\i\fs24 Pesach kitniyot}{\fs24 
 [forbidden food].  He consulted with his rabbi, and they gave permission not only for }{\i\fs24 matzoh}{\fs24  or potatoes or what, but }{\i\fs24 kitniyot}{\fs24 .  In other words, vegetables...
\par NL:\tab Baked beans
\par YM:\tab Beans which you wouldn't eat normally.  So, all these families were put up.  I think this was repeated in '15, '16, '15 and '16, because as the war went on, either the Russians pushed the Austro-Hungarians back, or the 
Austro-Hungarians pushed the Russians back, but the war went on in that part of the world, very close to us.
\par NL:\tab Very close.
\par YM:\tab Ya.
\par NL:\tab But you weren't involved in the...
\par YM:\tab We were never evacuated.  No.
\par NL:\tab ...war actually.
\par YM:\tab We had, of course, my mother's brother in particular, you may even know about him, Dr. Moishe Bolgar...
\par NL:\tab The, the...
\par YM:\tab Braun, original name.  His original name was Moishe Braun.  He was a lawyer by profession, and a first rate Hebrew novelist and writer and translator and, so he was at the battlefield all the time.
\par NL:\tab A soldier.
\par YM:\tab A soldier.  And we were under his, under this pressure that we were terribly scared for him.
\par NL:\tab For him.
\par YM:\tab He was like more than an uncle to us.  And we constantly were scared.  He was then, later on during the war he was the, the man responsible for a military newspaper called }{\i\fs24 Manilova}{\fs24 
, where he was still in great danger all the time, but at least he didn't have to stay in the first line and shoot at someone.
\par NL:\tab Yes, and, the end of the war meant changes for your community.  The peace treaty.  What were the territorial changes that involved your town?
\par YM:\tab No, first of all, before it came to the very end and before it was decided that our part of the world should belong to Czechoslovakia, or tha
t Czechoslovakia should be called into being at all, there were the--you know that the war in Hungary, especially where we belonged to, that part of Hungary came to an end by the White Revolution, White Flower Revolution, I don't know how that Flower is c
alled, but the Socialist movement became stronger, later on the Communist and here }{\i\fs24 Kun B\'e9la}{\fs24 
 comes in--the one we mentioned before--the Hungary became Communistic.  If it was one or the other, especially if it was Communistic, some people suffered from that.
\par NL:\tab And you were in what sector?
\par YM:\tab We were in, you mean as a party?  The sector of the land?
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab We were in the sector which was occupied once in awhile for shorter or longer periods by the Communist powers, I wouldn't even call it regime, beca
use it was no regime, or when others came who were stronger, so we were occupied by the White, they called them at the time...
\par NL:\tab The anti-Communists.
\par YM:\tab Ya.  By the Red; by the Rumanians; by the Czechs; by the, you name it, we were occupied by these powers.  And this, of course, went on in the end of 1917, '18, up to '19.  I became }{\i\fs24 bar mitzvah}{\fs24 
, as you can see it, in about '19.  After my }{\i\fs24 bar mitzvah}{\fs24 , I went to study in this Natsalutsch}{\fs24\super 1{\footnote \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar
