\par 
\par NL:\tab Now you were saying that your area was in the hands of a whole variety of occupation forces.  Do you have some impressions of any of those particular periods?  Did you suffer especially under any particular occupation, Cantor?
\par YM:\tab I myself as a child, of course, knew very little what's going on.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Because finally in 1917 I was still only 13 years old.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab However, what I remember and, these, I don't know if those are interesting observations or not, I remember, for i
nstance, that we had a dog, and the Rumanians came and shot the dog.  My brothers and sisters, they buried the dog and cried for the dog.  This made a very deep impression on me.  I know that the dog was laying around there dead [chuckling] and they didn'
t bury him, they wanted me to be home to, to bury him, too [chuckling].  So this kind of childish, eh...
\par NL:\tab Was this part of the anti-Jewish feeling on the part of the Rumanians, do you suppose?
\par YM:\tab No, it was rather to make the people feel that they are in charge.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab Now they went from house to house and picked up from flour, from sugar, from chickens, from soap, you name it, and they took it away from the family.  So this kind of thing, and this, and they were, it wasn't limited, this kind of 
activity was not limited to the Rumanians only, to any one who came, with the exception of the Czechs.
\par NL:\tab Ah yes.
\par YM:\tab They came well provided.  When they came, they came orderly, in an orderly fashion.  You know, of course, that the Czechs, many of them, 
were administrators of the Austro-Hungarian Empire already, and they knew very well how to handle people, most of them did.  Of course, in the moment they took over, things started to quiet down, and people knew that if they have a chicken, the soldiers w
o
n't come to take it away from them, or, if they had, let's say, geese, fat, or lard, or whatever, not like the Rumanians or the others, they won't take it away from them.  Stores started to open up again.  Materials in the stores started to appear.  Shoes
 were available.  For years no shoes were available in our vicinity.  You couldn't get a pair of shoes.  I will never forget it.  When I went to Nagyhalasz [phonetic] }{\i\fs24 Yeshiva}{\fs24 
, I still had those little slats made out of wood.  This is the way shoes were manufactured instead of soles.  So, this, these are my impressions.  Of course, what can a thirteen-year-old know...
\par NL:\tab Yes, yes.
\par YM:\tab ...in this kind of a boiling world.
\par NL:\tab Yes, did your parents ever talk to you or to the children about the Bolshevik period of occupation?
\par YM:\tab In my parents' mind, and I have to say this quite honestly, rightly or wrongly, Bolsheviks, because we were born, grew up, and lived in a different society, whatever was Red, whatever was Bolshevik, was poison.  They just couldn't, they 
couldn't even get to the point, I'm afraid, to consider it.
\par NL:\tab But this was how most Jews felt, I believe.
\par YM:\tab I would say so, yes.
\par NL:\tab Yes, there was a lot to fear.
\par YM:\tab Yes, a lot to fear.
\par NL:\tab A lot to fear.
\par YM:\tab A.  The financial standings of everyone were in danger, and second, the religion...
\par NL:\tab Anti-religious...
\par YM:\tab ...which was their life...
\par NL:\tab Of course.
\par YM:\tab ...which was their, their mainstay, was constantly in danger.
\par NL:\tab Of course.
\par YM:\tab And we heard that after, I don't know, we knew about all the troubles, let's say the,  the Russian Czar and his family and his generals gave to the Jewish population of Russia, we knew about all that, and we were sorry that they were killed.  But 
}{\i\fs24 Fonya-ganef}{\fs24  [Russian thief], as we called him in those days, and as he was called by the people who came to us, eh, we knew very well what happened to them, and we couldn't really, so to say, say }{\i\fs24 kaddish}{\fs24 
 after them.  We were sorry as human beings that they were killed, but we knew that religion is out, and no more }{\i\fs24 heder}{\fs24 , and no more }{\i\fs24 Mishnah}{\fs24 , and no more, no more, eh...
\par NL:\tab No more property, no more private property.
\par YM:\tab Right, yes, no more private property.
\par NL:\tab A lot to fear.
\par YM:\tab So from this you will see what our emotions and even logical considerations were.  Now my father, or mother, never sat down with us to have a political...
\par NL:\tab Discussion.
\par YM:\tab Political discussion.
\par NL:\tab [chuckles]
\par YM:\tab I mean in those days.  Among the boys I was the oldest, but my oldest sister wasn't even there.  She left Europe in 1913.  My younger sis
ter got married and she didn't live in the same place where we lived.  I really did not attend too many, and didn't even have a chance, to get the feeling--just what I heard superficially--and, of course, if Reb Moishe or Reb Chaim said that this is terri
ble, I had to think it is terrible.
\par NL:\tab And, and it was.  It was.  Uh, now in 1918, 1919, what was the political setup that affected your town, Cantor?
\par YM:\tab In 1918 and 1919, as I said, our part of the land changed owners, so to say, many many times, but in '19 I went to Nagyhalasz, to my first }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 
.  Nagyhalasz at the time, already, was Czechoslovakia.  And there was a great relaxation.  Our village was divided by the, rather, about four kilometers from our village we had a river called Tisza, which comes from the high, up in the...
\par NL:\tab Carpathian.
\par YM:\tab Carpathian mountains.  And, eh, flew through, close by to our river, to our village.  When I used to come home in the first }{\i\fs24 z'man--z'man}{\fs24  is a semester, six months, you know--when I used to come home, in '19 
or maybe '20, from Nagyhalasz, for a }{\i\fs24 Shabbes}{\fs24  to be home with my parents, we didn't need anything else, but a permit from the, Czechoslovakian police, let's say, or }{\i\fs24 Gendarmerie}{\fs24 
, or whatever it was, that we are citizens or...
\par NL:\tab Residents.
\par YM:\tab ...residents of this and this village.  And even if we were stopped, we could pass.
\par NL:\tab But your parents were technically within Hungary.
\par YM:\tab Technically, they were within Hungary, yes.  Because it wasn't decided that this wouldn't be Hungary any more at the time.  Whe
n then this other side of the Tisza was, eh, adopted to be also Czechoslovakia up to a certain point, then things relaxed in our village as well.  But in Nagyhalasz, really we didn't have this when I got there anymore, because Nagyhalasz, as such, because
 it was on the right hand side of this river, immediately was decided that this will be part of Podkarpatska Rus, yes, but it will belong as such, eh, to the Czechoslovakia.
\par NL:\tab Czechoslovakia.
\par YM:\tab Czechoslovakia.  Now you know that Czechoslovakia consisted of Podkarpatska Rus, Slovakia, Moravia, eh...
\par NL:\tab Bohemia.
\par YM:\tab Bohemia and so on.  So, therefore, this was just a part of it.  Where we lived was part of Podkarpatska Rus, all of it belongs, now, of course, to Russia.
\par NL:\tab To Russia, yes.  And did you live with a private family, or did you live in the }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 ?  Was there a dormitory?
\par YM:\tab This again is a very interesting story.  }{\i\fs24 Ich hab gegessen cost-teg}{\fs24  ["to support learning" families provided meals for }{\i\fs24 Yeshiva}{\fs24  students on different days], if you know what that is.
\par NL:\tab Yes, yes.
\par YM:\tab I eat a...
\par NL:\tab Eating days.
\par YM:\tab Right.  Every day at a different place.  I was just extremely lucky that my father, as a, a, as the owner of some...
\par NL:\tab Land.
\par YM:\tab ...land and so on had cattle to sell, and had sheep to sell, and had to buy things from, eh, materials for the farm and so on, so he had these friends, and I, just by coincidence, used to have my }{\i\fs24 cost-teg}{\fs24  at these families.

\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab As a matter of fact, my sister-in-law, Chava, who lives in Israel, her father was an associate in some way of my father, and I had a }{\i\fs24 cost-tug}{\fs24  [singular], a day, to get my lunch or dinner, whatever in their house.
\par NL:\tab Ah.
\par YM:\tab So that I knew Chava Eizdorfer even before she was born.
\par NL:\tab [Laughs].  Very interesting.  And this was a large }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 ?
\par YM:\tab It wasn't a large }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 
; it was a much bigger town than ours.  As I say it was the capital of this district, Ungvar, and, eh, I will say in Nagyhalasz, at the time probably have lived 350 Jewish, 400 Jewish families.  So that was already a big
 town.  Nagyhalasz had a beautiful, big synagogue, of course Orthodox, two, three }{\i\fs24 betai medrushim}{\fs24  [class-rooms], and it was a nice, nice town.  The }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24  as such was never big, and was never, there was never a }{
\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24  in Nagyhalasz in spite of the fact that the great Shmelcha Klein was the, the }{\i\fs24 Rov}{\fs24  in Nagyhalasz, it was never a }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24  town until Yosef Nehemiah Kornitz, }{\i\fs24 zichron l'bracha}{\fs24 
, came and organized this }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab Which consisted always of about 30, 35, less than 40 }{\i\fs24 bocherim}{\fs24  [young men].  And mainly youngsters.
\par NL:\tab Youngsters.
\par YM:\tab Young people, 14, 15, I myself studied in Nagyhalasz for two-and-a-half years; after that I already went to Ungvar, which was the capital city of Podkarpatska Rus, Uzhgorod, today it's called Uzhgorod.  Eh, and the }{\i\fs24 Rov}{\fs24 
 was the chief rabbi of Podkarpatska Rus, Erbavram Yosef Greenwald, he was a }{\i\fs24 haver}{\fs24  of my father in his father's }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24  in Ust.  So, I went to this }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 
 to study.  After that, in other words, we didn't spend, I don't know, the time in Nagyhalasz until we became ready for, for anything like }{\i\fs24 hora'ah}{\fs24 
 [teaching], or whatever it was.  We studied and got a good basic education there.  I myself was there, I think, for five }{\i\fs24 z'man}{\fs24  [semesters], that means two-and-a-half years.  After that I went to--started to study in Ungvar.
\par NL:\tab Oh my.  And, were there any secular studies involved, or...
\par YM:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab ...did you have a tutor for those?
\par YM:\tab In my, of course, in my village you couldn't, even if you did want to...
\par NL:\tab No.
\par YM:\tab ...go further than the fourth, maximum the sixth grade.
\par NL:\tab Grade.
\par YM:\tab Eh, so that when I came to Nagyhalasz and my uncle--this uncle which I mentioned before, was a great influence--to get some secular knowledge as well, I studied privately.  At the end of the season we took our exams i
n a private way.  Let me mention something very interesting.  I never in my life had any exercises, any kind of painting or drawing; that was just strange to me.  }{\i\fs24 Farbrenggen di tzait oif a solcha narishkaiten}{\fs24 
 [to spend time on such nonsense], who did it?  So, at the end, when I was prepared, ya, in Nagyhalasz, there was the middle }{\i\fs24 shule}{\fs24 
, and the [unclear] it was called, where you could get above the elementary school four grades, four years.  So, I wanted to have at least get that what I could.  I don't know if my father ever discussed this question with, eh...
\par NL:\tab Your uncle.
\par YM:\tab No, my uncle he did, but with my rebbe.
\par NL:\tab Oh.
\par YM:\tab Yes, you know, that was a big thing.
\par NL:\tab Of course.
\par YM:\tab }{\i\fs24 Hachutzoniyot}{\fs24  [outside studies] wasn't simple to study.  I don't know i
f he did or if he didn't, but he advised me, probably at the influence of my uncle, to go to A, B, C, D teachers, prepare with them, and at the end they gave us then, we went to school, that was a day assigned for...
\par NL:\tab Examinations.
\par YM:\tab For private examinations.  So, the man who gave me the exam in mathematics, and, eh, }{\i\fs24 tziur}{\fs24 , eh,
\par NL:\tab Penmanship?
\par YM:\tab No, eh, not penmanship, but you know, to...
\par NL:\tab Composition?
\par YM:\tab To eh, to draw something.
\par NL:\tab Oh.
\par YM:\tab Drawing.
\par NL:\tab Drawing.
\par YM:\tab You know, so he said, look, you did quite well in mathematics.  You did terribly, no, he said, you did terribly in this, my department and if you will pass mathematics, well, fine, I will let you pass.  If not, [laughs] you won't pass!
\par NL:\tab [Laughs]
\par YM:\tab [Laughs]
\par NL:\tab Yah, interesting.  So now, you stayed in this town for two-and-a-half years...
\par YM:\tab Two-and-a-half years.
\par NL:\tab And then?
\par YM:\tab Then I went to Ungvar.
\par NL:\tab That's...
\par YM:\tab U-N-G-V-A-R.
\par NL:\tab And that was in Hungary?
\par YM:\tab That was, that was, that was originally, originally it was Hungary.  At the time when I went there it was the capital city of Podkarpatska Rus.
\par NL:\tab And how do you spell Podkarpatska Rus?
\par YM:\tab  P-O-D, Karpatska as you spell, it's a separate word, of course.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab  Kar-Pat-Ski, just as I say it phonetically, Russ, R-U-S-S.}{\fs24\super 2{\footnote \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar
