  And this was the capital city of Podkarpatska Rus.  In, at the time, 13, 14, two-and-a-half years, I was about seventeen, eighteen years of age, and I got to Ungvar, maybe even less, I don't know, I stayed in Ungvar for four-and-a-half years.
\par NL:\tab Still studying?
\par YM:\tab Still studying, and only this.
\par NL:\tab At the }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24  there?
\par YM:\tab At the }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 .  There was a }{\i\fs24 yeshiva haramah}{\fs24 , it was a big }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 .  There were 300 }{\i\fs24 bocherim}{\fs24 , and there already it was divided in, eh, divisions and sub-divisions, younger }{
\i\fs24 bocherim }{\fs24 who studied [unclear] just this.  As I have mentioned before, }{\i\fs24 maidneshiiur}{\fs24  [phonetic] and so on, so, others who studied up to this and this point, later on others who came up to, I don't know, the }{\i\fs24 
horaah}{\fs24 , who, who stood for the }{\i\fs24 nisayon}{\fs24 , [exams] }{\i\fs24 paskan shailles}{\fs24  and so on.  There was, as I have said, this Erbavram Yosef Greenwald was my father's }{\i\fs24 haver}{\fs24  [friend] in his father's }{\i\fs24 
yeshiva}{\fs24 , and he was one, he was the chairman of the committee who examined for the }{\i\fs24 horaah}{\fs24 .  }{\i\fs24 Horaah}{\fs24 , is you know, all kinds of other things.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab But among other things it is, eh }{\i\fs24 issur veheter}{\fs24 , [prohibition permitted] you know, }{\i\fs24 kashres}{\fs24  [dietary laws], and }{\i\fs24 Shabbes}{\fs24  and }{\i\fs24 yom tov}{\fs24 
 [holiday] and so on, so, under his guidance, his son, who died here already, in Brooklyn, who was his successor later on, I studied with him, Yehoshua Greenwald, and together we were ordained, if I may call it that, to be }{\i\fs24 rabbonim}{\fs24 
, and to, that was not yet }{\i\fs24 haturis rabbonis}{\fs24  [ordination], it was just to }{\i\fs24 paskan}{\fs24  and to }{\i\fs24 paskan shailles}{\fs24  in }{\i\fs24 issur veheter}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab Mmm Hmm.
\par YM:\tab Up to }{\i\f31\fs24 simank\'ecfiyot}{\fs24 .  That was the way it went.  And that's the way, the way it worked.
\par NL:\tab That was the cycle.
\par YM:\tab The cycle, yes.  That was the highest.  That was the most, eh, progress, the highest grade, let's say, achieved.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab So this is what I finished in Ungvar.  From Ungvar I was, at the age of 19 and older, probably, drafted into the Czech army.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par YM:\tab I think we should stop here and now and we could probably, ya, and we will...
\par NL:\tab We'll continue, all right, thank you very much, eh.
\par NL:\tab We are continuing the interview with Cantor Mandel, March 3rd, 1982, Nora Levin interviewing.  Cantor Mandel, would you now tell us the circumstances under which you, went into the Czech army, and your experiences in the army?
\par YM:\tab I see, eh...[tape turns off briefly]
\par 
\par YM:\tab I'm sorry for this interruption.  You asked me to tell you how I got into the Czech army?  Of course I was drafted and, like anybody else, at the time [phone rings; pause]
\par NL:\tab All right.
\par YM:\tab Is this O.K.?  The draft into the Czech army went like everywhere else.  You had to register, and, the draft board saw you in March, for what I had to come home especially from my }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 , and I was found, eh, able to, to serve.

\par NL:\tab What year was this?
\par YM:\tab That was in 1924.  1924.  I then, when I was drafted, I went back to }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 
 for my last exams which I had to go through, and with that I started to look, maybe for a position for the High Holy Days, because draftees had to report October the 1st, and on October the 1st, was I think  }{\i\fs24 erev}{\fs24  or }{\i\fs24 
Rosh Hashanah}{\fs24 , I tried out in a few places.  Finally I, performed the services, I }{\i\fs24 davened}{\fs24 
, and served in Ruzomberok [phonetic], that's called Russaveit [phonetic] eh, where, eh, a high military official who was a physician who had a sanatorium in 
Detatra [phonetic] told me I shouldn't be concerned, he will give me proper documentation that I got sick on the way to Olm\'fc
tz where I had to, mail some letter that I had to report, and this would be accepted.  The only thing what will happen is that I wil
l have to serve a few days, and in this case it was ten days, after I am finished with my year-and-a-half of service.  It happened that way in 1926 I got out of this early Czech military service.  A very interesting thing and maybe worthwhile to mention j
u
st for one reason, how the Czech, who--how liberal and wonderful they were.  In the Czech army, any candidate for the priesthood, the rabbinate, or such, had the right to, after basic training, which everyone had to go through, and that was ten weeks, he 
h
ad the right to report or to request or was even asked if he wants to go to a school, school for military administration was one way, the second possibility was a school in different hospitals to learn and study and become a male nurse.  I chose the hospi
tals, the military nursing, and went through all kinds of courses, and finally I was placed in Olm\'fctz}{\b\fs24 , }{\fs24 which is a town, Olomoudz}{\fs24\super 3{\footnote \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar
