\par NL:\tab This is tape two, side two, continuing our interview with Cantor Mandel.
\par YM:\tab As I have told you before, when I initially started to plan to go to, as they called it at the time, Siberia [laughs]...
\par NL:[laughs]
\par YM:\tab My family called it Siberia, I couldn't give them a good reason why I want to go, because really I had, we had, all we needed for sharing }{\i\fs24 kavod}{\fs24  [respect], and }{\i\fs24 nachat}{\fs24 
 [gratification] and live in the same town with the parents; it was beautiful.  But why be in Riga--the }{\i\fs24 Grosse Chor Synagoge}{\fs24  was first of all the off
icial temple of the Jewry of Lettland.  [Latvia].  Second of all, my predecessor, not the immediate one, the immediate one was Herman Yadlovger [phonetic], as I said before, my predecessor there was Baruch Leib Rosowsky, }{\i\fs24 Hazan }{\fs24 
Rosowsky, which by the way was the father of the Rosowsky who worked so much on the }{\i\fs24\ul M'nigunei Hatam, Ta'amag Hanigunim}{\fs24  and so on...}{\fs24\super 7{\footnote \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar
\tx-360\tx0\tx720\tx792\tx1440\tx1584\tx2160\tx2376\tx2880\tx3168\tx3600\tx3960\tx4140\tx4320\tx4578\tx4752\tx5040\tx5544\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {7}{\fs24 \tab 
\tab \tab \tab   }{Solomon Rosowsky (1878-1962) composer and musicologist, wrote }{\ul The Cantillation of the Bible (Five Books of Moses}{.}}}{\fs24 
\par NL:\tab Ah, I see...
\par YM:\tab It's his father.  It's his father.  I met him once in New York.  He just couldn't let me go.
\par NL:\tab I can imagine.
\par YM:\tab That I was the successor of his father.  So, when I came back home after I }{\i\fs24 davened}{\fs24 
, and I wasn't engaged immediately because we had meetings and this, and that, and I didn't have the time to stay there for so long, so I went home to Yugoslavia.  I told my family the reas
ons I will go to Riga are as follows:  I know I have a lifetime agreement here which I won't--I will leave.  Ella,}{\i\fs24  zikronah livrachah}{\fs24 
, has a lifetime position at the state, true.  We have a beautiful, artistically furnished, beautiful apartment, true.  I will leave that.  But where I'm going is--Riga is near the }{\i\fs24 Kol Bach}{\fs24 .}{\fs24\super 8{\footnote \pard\plain 
\ql \li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx-360\tx0\tx720\tx792\tx1440\tx1584\tx2160\tx2376\tx2880\tx3168\tx3600\tx3960\tx4140\tx4320\tx4578\tx4752\tx5040\tx5544\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {8}{\fs24 \tab \tab \tab \tab   }{\ul Kol Bo}{ - everything within.}}}{\fs24 
  Can you imagine that in 1934, Riga had from kindergarten on, up to university, schools and high schools where the teaching language was Hebrew.  When our son was born, I will never forge
t it, we had a very dear friend Dr. Gurvich, a lawyer, and his wife was a physician, their children came up to my wife to visit her in the sanatorium where she gave birth, and with a bunch of Hebrew names, what kind of names, written in Hebrew, they gave 
to her.  This is the kind of, no, the fact that in the temple there was a }{\i\fs24 bet}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 hamidrash}{\fs24  [Talmudic school] where 150 people were sitting every morning and every afternoon }{\i\fs24 bain mincha and maariv}{\fs24 
 [between the late afternoon and evening prayers] and they studied Talmud.  The...
\par NL:\tab The intellectual...
\par YM:\tab The intellectual level, quality of Rigensen Jews, of Russian Jewry, I will say, of course, there were others, but...
\par NL:\tab In Riga...
\par YM:\tab ...was so high, was so high.  Riga had 60,000 Jews at the time, I think 60
0,000 inhabitants, and 60,000 Jews.  Every person spoke at least three, four languages, Yiddish, of course, Russian, of course, Latvian, of course, but many people spoke perfect, perfect Hebrew, German, English, French, and so on.  It was such a high leve
l, I always say if there would be a class to choose from, where to choose from, for leaders of Jewry, worldwide, it should definitely be this kind of Jewry, because their intellect, I mean the way they, they, they were }{\i\fs24 ber tzedakah}{\fs24 
.  Once a year we had an appeal for, I don't know, the }{\i\fs24 moshav zakanim}{\fs24  [old age home].  Once a year a beautiful banquet was arranged.  }{\i\fs24 Latkes}{\fs24  were served on Hanukkah, and that was the time.  But the }{\i\fs24 latkes}{
\fs24  had a hole.  Three, four sentences were necessary to tell the people: "}{\i\fs24 Meine tyere friynt mir huben lecher, Der moshav zakanim hot nit genug gelt}{\fs24 ."}{\fs24\super 9{\footnote \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar
\tx-360\tx0\tx720\tx792\tx1440\tx1584\tx2160\tx2376\tx2880\tx3168\tx3600\tx3960\tx4140\tx4320\tx4578\tx4752\tx5040\tx5544\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {9}{\fs24 \tab 
\tab \tab \tab   }{My dear friends, there are holes.  The Old-Age Home does not have enough money.}}}{\fs24   Money was flowing in like you can't imagine.
\par NL:\tab What was the chief economic, or what were the chief economic occupations of Jews in Riga?
\par YM:\tab As you well know, rubber industry was great.  Clothing industry was great.  Business, exports...
\par NL:\tab Merchandising...
\par YM:\tab Immense.  And they always say that where our }{\i\fs24 sechel}{\fs24  [brains-common sense], our intellect, stops, the Lithuanian Jew--the ones I was with--his intellect starts there.  They are such }{\i\fs24 khokhomim}{\fs24  [wise ones].  Such }
{\i\fs24 Talmidey khokhomim}{\fs24  [learned wise scholars].  Such educated people, that I have never, I mean, I lived with all kinds of people...
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab My own homeland, and eh, Hungary had quite a few nice }{\i\fs24 Talmidey khokhomim}{\fs24 , but there it was more on a general basis.
\par NL:\tab Very high.
\par YM:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab Excellence.
\par YM:\tab Ya.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab High excellence.
\par NL:\tab So you stayed just for a short time and returned home?
\par YM:\tab Eh, no.
\par NL:\tab What did you do...
\par YM:\tab I stayed, I stayed until trouble became very prevalent...
\par NL:\tab Oh.
\par YM:\tab Around Riga.
\par NL:\tab Oh, you, your wife and you then removed to Riga?
\par YM:\tab We moved to Riga, and were in Riga from 1934, beginning of 1934, '5, '6, three years.
\par NL:\tab I see.  And did your wife resume teaching?
\par YM:\tab She did not resume teaching.
\par NL:\tab No.
\par YM:\tab She had worked in the Hebrew school, not as a professional.  She had remedials, like, if children needed help, she gave it to them, 'cause she knew Hebrew at the time already quite well.
\par NL:\tab And I would like the name of your son, Cantor.
\par YM:\tab My son's name is Immanuel Zvi.
\par NL:\tab And he was born in what year?
\par YM:\tab He was born in 1936.
\par NL:\tab In Riga?
\par YM:\tab In Riga, May, I guess.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Now, we moved to Riga, we lived there in Riga, and it was a continuation of }{\i\fs24 gan eden}{\fs24  [Garden of Eden], bea
utiful.  We had no difficulties.  Finally in the Baltic States, as you know, that's the closest to Germany, there tremendous fights and border clashes, and real trouble started.  And the Germans became stronger and stronger, as I don't have to tell you, i
t started in Austria, and then continued in other places.  Finally, there, it became very dangerous.
\par NL:\tab Would you say the seat of it was in the universities, or among the lower classes, or simultaneous?
\par YM:\tab I would say it was simultaneous.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par YM:\tab Yes, simultaneous.  Because I wasn't out in the Gdansk, for instance, these places which were the corridor, the so-called corridor, but there daily clashes came.
\par NL:\tab Between the Nazis and anti-Nazis?
\par YM:\tab Between the Nazis and anti-Nazis.  Jewish stores were obliterated.  Jewish people were beaten up.  Some disappeared, and the danger became immensely big.
\par NL:\tab Excuse me, was there an economic problem in the country, generally, at that time?
\par YM:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab No.
\par YM:\tab No, there was no...
\par NL:\tab No depression.
\par YM:\tab No kind of, no depression.
\par NL:\tab No depression.
\par YM:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab So that was...
\par YM:\tab Uhrmanish was the president at the time, of the country, and it was very well-organized...
\par NL:\tab Prosperous.
\par YM:\tab Prosperous, a good country.  And the Jews maintained the prosperity for [unc
lear].  The government, you couldn't detect at the time in the government any Nazism, though some people who, for instance this Guraviches, who he was a lawyer, and dealt with the courts and so on, he said yes, there is antisemitism outside in the world. 
 
We don't know about it because we live a sheltered life.  But he, and in the newspapers you, you could see it.  What happened in 1936 is maybe what saved us.  In 1936 my brother, my younger brother, who lived in Yugoslavia, got married, and that was in Ap
ril of 1936, Yoel, was his name.
\par NL:\tab Yoel.
\par YM:\tab Yoel.  And I came to his wedding from Riga to Yugoslavia.  My wife was expecting, so she didn't make this trip, she stayed there, and--my father-in-law, when I traveled, was in  Yugoslavia, so I visited with th
em as well--he told me that he was in Budapest some time ago, and the Secretary General, Eppler, asked him where I am.  He heard me once }{\i\fs24 daven}{\fs24 
